Resolves #2022

This PR introduces a new key provider that you can configure as follows:

```hcl
terraform {
  encryption {
    key_provider "external" "foo" {
      command = ["./some_program", "some_parameter"]
    }
  }
}
```

This external program can provide OpenTofu with key material. It has to perform 3 steps.

### Step 1: Writing a header

The external program must write the following header to the standard output in a single line, followed by a newline:

```json
{"magic":"OpenTofu-External-Key-Provider","version":1}
```

### Step 2: Reading the input

The external program must read the input data from stdin matching the following JSON:

```json
{
  "external_data": {
    "key1": "value1",
    "key2": "value2"
  }
}
```

### Step 3: Writing the output

The external program must write the key material to the standard output in the following format:

```json
{
  "key": {
    "encryption_key": "newly generated base64-encoded encryption key",
    "decryption_key": "base64-encoded decryption key, if input meta was present, omitted otherwise"
  },
  "meta": {
    "external_data": {
      "key1": "value1",
      "key2": "value2"
    }
  }
}
```

## Chaining with PBKDF2

You can also use this key provider in conjunction with the PBKDF2 provider. This will allow you to read a password from a password manager and supply it as a passphrase:

```hcl
terraform {
  encryption {
    key_provider "external" "foo" {
      command = ["./some_program", "some_parameter"]
    }
    key_provider "pbkdf2" "passphrase" {
      chain = key_provider.external.foo
    }
  }
}
```

## Target Release

1.10.0

